\par\plain {Will and Madeleine sank onto a weathered bench outside the library, their postering marathon taking its toll. The late afternoon sun cast long shadows, painting the campus in a warm, melancholic glow. A cool breeze rustled through the nearby trees, carrying the faint scent of freshly cut grass and offering a momentary respite from the emotional turmoil churning within them. Each clutched a condensation-slicked beverage, the chilled liquid a small comfort against the burning worry in their hearts.}
\par\plain {Will stared down at his drink, his brow furrowed in a mixture of self-reproach and despair. "I should have known, Madeleine," he muttered, his voice heavy with regret. "My own bandmates... part of the Black Hand. How could I have been so blind?"}
\par\plain {Madeleine reached out, placing a gentle hand on his shoulder. "It's not your fault, Will," she said softly. "They were good at hiding their true nature. No one could have expected this."}
\par\plain {Will shook his head, unconvinced. "But I should have seen it. We were a band for a year, for crying out loud! There were signs, little things that just didn't sit right. I ignored them. And now Ashley..." He choked back a sob, the word "gone" hanging heavy in the air.}
\par\plain {Squeezing his shoulder gently, Madeleine offered words of comfort. "Will, listen to me," she said firmly. "You can't blame yourself for this. You're not a mind reader. No one expects you to see through people's lies, especially when they're so deeply woven."}
\par\plain {A heavy silence descended upon them, broken only by the distant sounds of students hurrying to their evening classes. Finally, after a long moment, Madeleine spoke again, her voice softer now, laced with a hint of curiosity.}
\par\plain {"You cared about her a lot, didn't you, Will?" she asked, a knowing smile playing on her lips.}
\par\plain {Will met her gaze, a flicker of surprise crossing his features. He hesitated for a moment, then a small, genuine smile tugged at the corner of his mouth. "Yeah," he admitted sheepishly. "More than I ever admitted, even to myself."}
\par\plain {His smile broadened, tinged with a bittersweet fondness. "She could be a real pain in the neck in class, I'll give her that," he chuckled, a single tear tracing a path down his cheek. "But you know what? She was special. Like a\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8230\'85 a firecracker, always bursting with energy and life. And yeah," he continued, his voice firm now, a newfound determination replacing the self-pity, "she's my best friend.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {Madeleine returned his smile, her own eyes shining with fierce determination. \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Then we will find her.\u8221\'94 }
